{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:00:43.698Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Defining Core Data Structures**\n\nI've nailed down the core data structure elements. It appears that `id`, `created_at`, and `updated_at` are non-negotiable for all use cases. The `client_id` field has surfaced as optional, though the data type needs careful handling for the DynamoDB implementation, as a string representation seems necessary.\n\n\n**Refining Integer ID Strategy**\n\nI've got a fantastic strategy for those integer IDs! We can use a deterministic hash code from the email address itself. This ensures uniqueness and simplifies mapping, making the whole system more robust. Also, I've got the `created_at` and `updated_at` fields figured out. They'll be Python `datetime` objects, so they're fully compatible!\n\n\n**Constructing DynamoUser Details**\n\nI've sketched out the new `DynamoUser` constructor, and it has come along nicely. I've handled defaulting `full_name`, `name`, `role`, `status`, and `is_active`, including data type considerations for the `client_id` field. Now, I'm working on assigning the deterministic integer `id`, which may involve mapping pre-existing emails.\n\n\n**Implementing Known IDs and Times**\n\nI've worked out a strategy for the `id`, leaning on a dictionary of known values and hashing for new emails, for generating the data. Also, I have a clear plan on how to deal with the `created_at` and `updated_at` timestamps, handling string parsing and defaulting to UTC now, if needed.\n\n\n**Handling Time Conversions**\n\nI'm now focusing on ensuring consistent and robust handling of `created_at` and `updated_at` fields. I'm carefully managing the various input types and defaulting to UTC now, if needed, along with ensuring correct formatting during object serialization. This also includes proper error handling.\n\n\n"}}
