{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:01:09.788Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Investigating Database Seeding**\n\nI've observed that the `setup_database()` function calls `seed_db(reset=True)`. My focus shifted when the database didn't populate as expected. I'm now examining `backend/app/seed.py`, specifically lines 1 to 20, to understand the discrepancy in behavior. My efforts center on diagnosing why the seed function did not execute as expected.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:01:11.594Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Clarifying Data Synchronization**\n\nI've realized the `AuthService.create_user()` function now writes only to the DynamoDB mock, not SQLite, because it uses the DynamoDB users repository. This explains why the SQLite database remains empty after seeding, despite the seed function running. My main focus is now on synchronizing data between the DynamoDB mock and SQLite. I'm considering options: synchronizing the databases directly, updating `seed_db()` to populate SQLite, making the repositories write to both, or updating `AuthService.create_user()` to write to both.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T21:01:13.109Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Implementing Dual-Write Strategy**\n\nI'm pursuing a dual-write approach. I believe that by modifying `AuthService.create_user()` to write to both the DynamoDB mock and SQLite database, I can address both requirements. The method appears to provide a SQLAlchemy session. I'll evaluate how to seamlessly integrate SQLite updates within the existing DynamoDB write operation. It seems feasible to include the SQLite `User` record creation when a valid session is provided.\n\n\n","redacted":false}}
