ite `User` records. I've also added a check for an existing email in SQLite.\n\n\n**Analyzing Data Source Consistency**\n\nI'm realizing that `seed.py` creates clients and other entities like projects and operations directly in SQLite, bypassing the API's usual data source. This is creating a data consistency problem when the API routes are queried, specifically if the routes expect their data from the DynamoDB mock, which may be unpopulated! I'm now exploring how the API routes are retrieving data during tests, given this discrepancy. I'm focusing on the `portal_items_repo` and how it interacts with different data sources during seeding and testing.\n\n\n**Synchronizing Data Sources**\n\nI've realized the implications of the direct SQLite seeding. The DynamoDB mock remains untouched, leading to inconsistencies. Now, I believe I've struck gold with a sync function during DynamoDB client initialization. This function, triggered within `seed_mock_database()` in `dynamodb_client.py`, will read data from SQLite and populate the DynamoDB mock tables. I'll import `SessionLocal` to open a session and then transfer data between the databases. Specifically, I'll read `User` and `ClientAccount` records from SQLite and add them into the respective mock lists. This will ensure 100% synchronization.\n\n\n**Implementing Data Synchronization**\n\nI'm now focusing on a `sync_with_sqlite()` function to ensure seamless data transfer. I'll read all relevant data—`User`, `ClientAccount`, `Project`, and other entities from the SQLite database. Then, I will translate these data points into the format required for the DynamoDB mock tables. I'll be meticulously adding these records to the appropriate mock lists within the settings, ensuring complete and reliable synchronization between the databases, no matter what seeding or modification occurs within SQLite, thereby maintaining 100% consistency. I will be sure to add exception handling to this sync function.\n\n\n**Populating DynamoDB Mock**\n\nI'm now synchronizing data into the DynamoDB mock. I'm focusing on populating the `User` table. I'm querying SQLite to get the `User` and `ClientAccount` records. I'm converting this data into a format compatible with the DynamoDB mock tables. This involves iterating through each user record and transforming it to the DynamoDB mock format before adding it to the respective mock lists. I'm ensuring all user-related data from SQLite is accurately mirrored.\n\n\n**Transferring Data Structures**\n\nI'm now completing the sync process for `Project` data. I've populated the `User` table and am focused on transforming SQLite's `Project` records into a structure usable for the DynamoDB mock. This involves creating a series of dictionaries for each project, populating keys like `PK`, `SK`, `GSI1PK`, `GSI1SK`, `id`, `client_id`, `name`, `phase`, `status`, `health`, and `owner`. I'm using a loop to iterate through each project from the database, building the corresponding dictionaries and appending them to the mock list.\n\n\n**Completing Data Mapping**\n\nI'm now implementing the final stage, transferring `AgentOperation` and `DocumentItem` records. The same mapping strategy from the `Project` synchronization will be applied. I'm taking the records from SQLite and preparing them for the DynamoDB mock. I'm focusing on crafting dictionaries, carefully mapping each field like `PK`, `SK`, `GSI1PK`, `GSI1SK`, `id`, `client_id`, `project_id`, `name`, `agent_type`, `status`, `health`, `owner`, and `governance_status` for the AI Operations. Then, I will focus on populating the `DocumentItem` mock table.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing Data Synchronization**\n\nI'm now completing the sync process. I'm taking the SQLite records for `DocumentItem` and `Invoice`, crafting their dictionary representations, and adding them to the DynamoDB mock. I'm focusing on ensuring all relevant data points—like document IDs, client IDs, and invoice details—are correctly transferred. I'll meticulously review the mappings for correctness to ensure that the mocked data is an exact reflection of the data in SQLite. I'm making sure all the data, even `invoice_number`, is accurately stored.\n\n\n**Mapping Additional Data**\n\nI'm now focusing on implementing the data transfer for Support Tickets. I will carefully craft dictionaries and transfer the relevant fields, ensuring seamless integration. I'll include things like `id`, `client_id`, `project_id`, `title`, `category`, and `status`. I'll pay close attention to the keys used and make sure the data transfers correctly. The next step will be mapping governance items.\n\n\n\n**Synchronizing Governance Data**\n\nI'm now synchronizing Governance items. I'm taking the records from SQLite and constructing dictionary representations, including fields such as `id`, `client_id`, `project_id`, `title`, `severity`, and `status`. Now, I'm thinking about the best time to call the sync function. Should I run it on every query and scan in Mock mode, when lists are requested, or, perhaps best, inside `MockTable.scan()` and `MockTable.query()` automatically?\n\n\n"}}
